The paper deals with the dot-depth hierarchy, which is a classification of star-free languages, and its relationship with the quantifier alternation hierarchy of first-order logic over finite words. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Formal Languages and Automata Theory (cs.FL) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses fragments of existential first-order logic without min- or max-predicate, which falls under the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category. The effective algebraic characterizations of the language classes also suggest a connection to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The decidability of the membership problem for dot-depth 1/2 and dot-depth 1 involves combinatorial proofs, which could be relevant to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. Finally, the paper's focus on language fragments and their correspondence with logic fragments suggests a connection to Information Theory (cs.IT).
